Not at all.  What I am suggesting is to ignore statements like this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> As I find a Xloc about 12 people in Wraith accuse me of ninja looting some Plate Arms in Kael.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If someone is this upset over accusations pointed at them why not list their names? What purpose is it to &quot;estimate&quot; (read blow out of proportion) the number of people and then blame the entire guild anyway?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A few people in Wraith told me that their whole guild petitioned me<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Once again, what good can become of vague statements like this?  How can Wraith account for their actions if pertinent information is left out?  If you have a legitimate beef state the facts not obscure references to people and actions.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I really did not appreciate all the hatefull tells I recieved from Wraith<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The person did not care to take a log of the event?  A screenshot?  And again ... &quot;hatefull tells&quot;  by who? What did they say?<br>
<br>
<br>
So my response is not that we should ignore history.  My response is that we should examine our accounts of history before we accept it as truth.  Vague accounts with no points of reference to corroborate the story should be treated with a grain of salt.<br>
<br>
Too often I see people ready to bash a guild (in this case Wraith) based on untruth and the historical bashing of those before them instead of forming their own opinions.  I am not Wraith but my association and interaction with them has been fantastic and not limited to a few minutes in the arena.<br>
<br>
Base your opinions of a person/guild on your experience with them and history.<br>
Beware judging a person/guild by taking solely the vague representations of anothers experiences as truth.<br>
